b'' b'[referring to mary]' b'she was immaculately conceived, and so never subject to original sin,' b'but also never committed a personal sin in her whole life. this was' b'possible because of the special degree of grace granted to her by god.' b' skipping......' b"i don't particularly object to the idea of the assumption, or the" b'perpetual virginity (both of which i regard as catholic dogma about' b'which i will agree to disagree with my catholic brothers and sisters' b'in christ), and i even believe in the virgin birth of jesus, but' b"this concept of mary's sinlessness seems to me to be at odds with" b'the rest of christian doctrine as i understand it.' b'' b'the catholic church has an entirely different view of mary than do' b'"most" other christian churches (those with parallel beliefs' b'notwithstanding). christ, by most accounts, is the only sinless' b'person to ever live. i too, have trouble with a sinless mary' b'concept just.' b'as for the related issue of the "original" sin only adam and' b'eve will answer for that one. my children do not answer for my sins,' b'certainly i only answer for mine.' b'--' b'larry autry' b'silicon graphics, st. louis' 